{
  "doc_id": "3944",
  "text": "(Orthologs are genes that have diverged only through speciation, as opposed to paralogs, which are genes that have diverged after duplication within a single species.) Orthologous gene displacement has been documented for several functional categories of genes, including enzymes in the citric acid cycle [CITATION_1] , antibiotic resistance genes such as variant dihydrofolate reductases [CITATION_2] , and even the genes comprising the entire type III secretion system apparatus [CITATION_3] . However, these orthologous displacements are difficult to detect with existing techniques [CITATION_4] . Therefore, we hypothesized a more-powerful HGT-detection method based on changes in Q to be especially useful for detecting orthologous gene displacement.",
